{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cfce7430-a98f-48dd-b011-ac273f55ccdf","content":"The environment has `dotnet` but not `dotnet-dump`. Here's what I recommend:\n\n### To analyze your dump, use `dotnet-dump analyze`\n\nI can install it for you:\n```\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n```\n\nThen run:\n```\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your.dmp\n```\n\nKey commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Print last exception (start here!) |\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n\n### Typical workflow\n1. **`pe`** — shows the exception type, message, and stack trace\n2. **`clrthreads`** — find threads with exceptions\n3. **`setthread <id>`** + **`clrstack`** — inspect specific threads\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` and start analyzing? If so, please share the **path to your .dmp file**.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ce97468-29ed-46d2-a64c-6f18e424b6a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The environment has `dotnet` but not `dotnet-dump`. I can install `dotnet-dump` as a global tool to help analyze the dump. But first, I should ask where the dump file is located since it wasn't found in the working directory.","outputTokens":341,"requestId":"2042:3131A1:64F1493:6DD8204:69F013A4"},"id":"e80b8d8f-9fc7-46f6-a54a-a1a68794a99a","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:55:58.434Z","parentId":"f8ba5e63-846e-4104-ad8d-2cfb0d39e9f7"}
